post_text:
Breaking news!

Thanks to a nationwide waiver that was granted, we are able to serve meals to ALL children ages 2 to 18! No meal cards needed!

Effective, 9/1/20, free meals are available to children 2-18 years old.

All families welcome, not restricted to RCSD students

No meal card is required

Students do not have to be present

Monday-Wednesday meal pick up (other options are available by asking kitchen staff or calling 650-423-2279)

At this time, our hours remain the same.

An important update for families as we work together creating a safe learning environment for all :

During last night's RCSD Board of Trustees public meeting, RCSD staff presented to the School Board the district’s Roadmap to Reopening my School plan for the 2020-21 school year.

The School Board reached consensus to start the school year with the Distance Learning Model for at least until the end of the first trimester, which typically ends before the Thanksgiving break.

District staff will bring the proposal to the School Board next week, Wednesday, July 22, 6pm, for consideration and final Board adoption.

Please stay tuned for more information.

The application period for P-EBT has been extended to July 15. This program provides extra grocery funding for students who are normally able to get free or reduced price school meals.

Please visit https://ca.p-ebt.org/en/ to apply if you are eligible and have not done so yet.

This is a joint program of the California Departments of Education and Social Services.

Applying for P-EBT does not affect a child's ability to receive meals at RCSD's pickup sites.

Beginning July 1, the RCSD pickup sites will be Hoover and Garfield (Mon thru Wed, 10:30 am to 11:30 am).

During the public Board of Trustees meeting on Wednesday, June 17, 2020, a revised timeline for the final approval of the school district’s Neighborhood Schools Boundary Change Study was adopted.

The new timeline allows additional time for the district demographer to create a third scenario and for the community to provide feedback on the new map before final School Board approval.

To learn more about the new timeline, please visit https://www.smore.com/r8kx5

The revised timeline is as follows:

Monday, July 6, 2020 -- Third map and community input form uploaded to district website

Friday, July 10, 2020 -- community input form on district website closes

Wednesday, July 22, 2020 -- 2nd Public Hearing

Wednesday, July 29, 2020 -- Final Board Adoption

Redwood City Public Library hosts its Summer Learning Challenge from June 1st through August 31st. Sign-ups begin June 1st at www.redwoodcity.org/summerlearning

Children 18 years and younger will receive a free book for signing up, earn free prizes when they finish, and be entered into a drawing for a $1,000 scholarship. The child must be a resident of Redwood City or North Fair Oaks to be eligible to win.

Adults who finish the Summer Learning Challenge will earn a chance to win gift cards from local businesses.

April is National Poetry Month!

Children (and adults!) may have a lot of feelings about being away from school and the many other changes in our communities.

Writing and reading poems are great ways to express how one is feeling, and to understand that others have these feelings too.

Poetry Foundation has a selection of poems for children to enjoy at bit.ly/2xVr12G , or encourage them to write their own.

Device check-out process for 2nd Grade students will take place this week. Please note that specific days and times have been scheduled for specific schools to practice social distancing and avoid large crowds and lines at the District Office. The schedule ( bit.ly/3dLGkv2 ) is as follows:

Adelante Selby Spanish Immersion School and Garfield Community School:
Wednesday, April 1, 9 am-noon

Henry Ford Elementary School and Roosevelt School:
Wednesday, April 1, 1-4pm

Hoover Community School:
Thursday, April 2, 9 am-noon

Clifford School, Roy Cloud School, and Orion Alternative Elementary School:
Thursday, April 2, 1-4pm

(Please note: Taft Community School 2nd graders do not need to check-out a Chromebook as the school is using a different learning format.)

The check-out process will take place at the District Office, which is located at 750 Bradford St. in Redwood City at the specific times listed above.

The student does not have to be present but the parent will need a form of identification and sign for a Chromebook that will be returned to school.

Reminder:

Starting Monday March 30, meal pick-ups are from 10:30- 11:30 on weekdays.

The district has added Roosevelt School as a fourth meal pick-up site.

Any child who is under 18-years old can get both breakfast and lunch. The child does not need to be a student in RCSD and does not need to be present at pick up.

Frozen entrees will be provided as drive-thru brown bags, which means families can pick them up and take them home to heat up.

Families are asked not to park or get out of their cars as staff will be out front ready with the meals to be picked up. Families just need to pop the trunk and staff will place the meals in the trunk.

All families will need to comply with staff to maintain their physical distance.

Important updates to meal services! Please spread the word.

Beginning March 25, lunch will be a frozen entree that must be heated at home. Heating instructions will be provided.

Starting Monday, March 30, meal pick-up time will be 10:30 am to 11:30 am (for both breakfast and lunch).

Where: Henry Ford, Garfield, Roosevelt and Hoover sites.

Children and Youth 18 and under do not need to be present for complimentary meal pick up

*********

Your child does not need to be a student in RCSD to pick up a free school meal.

Meals will be provided as drive-thru brown bags, which means families can pick them up at the school’s main front entrance and take them home. Both breakfast and lunch can be picked up at the same time.

Do not park or get out of your cars, staff will be out front ready with the meals for you to pick up. You just need to pop your trunk and staff will place the meals in your trunk.

You are welcome to walk to the schools; however, please comply with staff directions, as they will be practicing social distancing.

Social distancing practices can help stop the spread of infections by creating space between us.

While the coronavirus is still spreading, all of us need to take a "better safe than sorry" approach and distance ourselves from everyone at all times, including when picking up meals or learning devices.

post_text:
Free sack lunch will be available for all youth (18 and younger) from 10 a.m. to 12 p.m. on weekdays at the following locations:

Hoover Community School
Henry Ford Elementary School
Garfield Community School

Drive-up in your vehicle. Pop your trunk from inside if possible, and lunch will be brought to you to take home based on the number of children present. Children must be present, as required by USDA.

Please be mindful of blocking streets or sidewalks. We hope to flow cars just as we do at pick up and drop off times.

It is OK to "walk-thru" and take home lunches. We want to make sure all children are getting a meal, while still minimizing contact and practicing social distancing as recommended by the public health departments.

Thank you!

It’s Climate Survey season! The school climate survey measures many aspects of the educational environment, including perceptions of school safety, family engagement, and the overall social and learning environment.

Your anonymous feedback provides a representative picture of the school in order to identify specific strengths, as well as areas for improvement within a school.

The Big Lift
January 23 at 9:59 PM ·

We have LIFTOFF!! This week we celebrate Redwood City School District and their generous community partners!

The Big Lift Redwood City program community members have incredibly enriching experiences thanks to strong partnerships. Programs serving Big Lift kids and families include Insectarium, Imagination Playground, Sol Soup, and San Mateo County Libraries that offered robotics and coding opportunities providing terrific learning and engagement! Finally, Second Harvest of Silicon Valley serves much appreciated summertime daily snacks.

Congratulations to Redwood City School District Big Lift teachers, leaders, and partners for creating such a holistic learning environment!

#LiftWithUs
#summerlearning

post_text:
It's National Mentoring Month! Who is a mentor?

A mentor is someone who teaches or gives help, advice, and positive examples to a less experienced and often younger person.

Children's first mentors are often parents or guardians, family members, teachers, school staff, librarians, and after school providers.

Share your positive mentorship story below!

#MentoringMonth

shared_text:
The Big Lift
December 5, 2019 at 11:10 PM ·

We have LIFTOFF!! This week we celebrate Education Specialist Danielle Webb and Redwood City School District preschools and teachers!

Ms. Webb helps teachers identify the needs of children and their families. Her detailed classroom observations help teachers identify children’s specific learning needs and how to best meet those needs. Additionally, Ms. Webb supports teachers work with families to create a preschool-family partnership for each child’s physical, intellectual, social, and emotional development.

Congratulations to Ms. Webb and Redwood City School District preschools and teachers for creating such an insightful and collaborative learning environment!

#LiftWithUs
#preschool

San Mateo County Office of Education
